    "r1_date": "https://www.instagram.com/p/DVeLpYADBHj/",
    "r1_topic": "A1 vs B1 vocab set",
    "r1_notes": "She starts the reel simply by saying \"A1 kontra B1\". It's okay she wants to jump right in, however for me as a native speaker the term \"kontra\" sounds odd. I personally would have used the term 'gegen' or even 'versus' despite the fact that it's an anglicism, even though I would understand caution with non-german vocab, I merely want to note it'd be at least natural sounding. The following terminology she presents e.g. fragen -> sich erkundigen is useful and a good idea, but the terms she compares are often only associated but misleading to be taken as exact replacer. For example she presents B1 'Gebäude' as upgrade to A1 'Haus', but one needs to understand the broader context and it makes it all a bit of a slippery slope in my perception. Her pronunciation is quite okay, but flawed, and she wrongly pronounces the -ig ending in southern German style which I find problematic because she should teach Hochdeutsch.",
    "r1_engagement": "57 / 0",
    "r2_date": "https://www.instagram.com/p/DVRflDjjHuV/",
    "r2_topic": "Restaurant ordering roleplay",
    "r2_notes": "I like the idea and I have to say even though she is not sovereign as an actress (too much hesitation in character when ordering food) it is a helpful reel to learners. I have to note though that she said \"Ich hätt' gerne\" which is very odd, because a native speaker would either articulate the entire sentence cleanly or if elliptic they would say \"Ich hätte gern\", but not the variation she presented - it may exist but I feel like it is way less common.",
